initial_story:
We perhaps should not be surprised that the prime minister has seized upon an extrapolation of Thursday's local election results that pointed to the prospect that the general election could result in a hung parliament in which Labour would be the largest party.

Such a scenario, he argued, would mean that Sir Keir Starmer would be "propped up in Downing Street" by the SNP, the Liberal Democrats, and the Greens.

Many Conservative MPs (and indeed Labour ones too) believe that a poster their party ran in the 2015 election, when the polls were pointing to a hung parliament, showing the then Labour leader, Ed Miliband, in the pocket of the former SNP leader, Alex Salmond, played a key role in delivering the Conservatives a surprise overall majority.

Whether or not that is what happened is not easy for analysts to say. However, British Election Study data collected at the time did not show any marked swing away from Labour among those who came to believe that Mr Miliband would be willing to do a deal with the SNP.

But, in any event, how realistic is it to use the share of the vote won by the parties in local elections to anticipate what might happen in an immediate general election? There are certainly two potential difficulties.

Although the ups and downs in party performance in local elections often run in parallel with the rises and falls in party support in the polls, some people (around one in five) vote differently in local elections than they would in a general election.

As a result the divergence between the level of support parties win in a local election and how well they would perform in a general election has become more marked.

Nowadays the Liberal Democrats consistently outperform their national standing in the local ballot boxes. The same has also come to be true of the Greens, while independent candidates have also enjoyed some notable success in recent years. Labour, in contrast, often do less well in local elections.

Meanwhile, the party political battle in Scotland is now very different from that in England - and the outcome of the current battle north of the border between Labour and the SNP could be crucial to the result of the next election. English local elections do not tell us much about what will happen north of the border.

These developments have made discerning the implications of local elections for the outcome of a general election more difficult.

At the same time, there are two particular features of the results of this year's local elections that make it especially difficult.

First, the polls suggest that more people who voted Conservative in 2019 have now switched to Reform than to Labour. But Reform were only on the ballot paper in one in six council wards. So, it may well be the case that people who would vote Reform if there had been a Reform candidate locally stuck with the Tories instead.

Certainly, Conservative support fell more heavily where Reform did stand. In the BBC's sample of key wards the party's support fell by 19 points in these wards - compared with 11 points in wards where Reform did not stand. Labour, in contrast, did rather better where Reform stood.

That 19-point drop matches the 19-point fall in the average level of Conservative support in the polls since May 2021. That figure may represent a better guide to the Conservatives' immediate prospects in a general election.

Second, the local election results confirm the message from last year's contests that the geography of party support has changed to the Conservatives' disadvantage.

The party's support fell more heavily in wards it was trying to defend.

At the same time, some voters seemingly voted for whichever party was best placed to defeat the Conservatives locally. Labour's support increased most (at the expense of the Liberal Democrats) in wards where they started off second to the Conservatives, while the Liberal Democrats advanced most (and Labour did less well) in wards where were the principal challengers locally.

Indeed, it is these two patterns that help explain why the Conservative Party lost nearly one in two of the council seats it was trying to defend. Conservative MPs would be unwise to assume that the same fate could not also befall them.

Sir John Curtice is Professor of Politics, University of Strathclyde, and Senior Fellow, National Centre for Social Research and 'The UK in a Changing Europe'. He is also co-host of the Trendy podcast.
stories: However, it is worth noting that the prime minister's argument that a hung parliament would lead to Labour being propped up by the SNP, the Liberal Democrats, and the Greens is not as straightforward as it seems.
This is because the SNP has already ruled out forming a coalition with Labour, and the Liberal Democrats have made it clear that they would not support a Labour government in any circumstances.

As a result, it seems increasingly likely that Boris Johnson will be returned to Downing Street, either as the leader of a minority Conservative government or as the head of a minority government propped up by the Democratic Unionist Party (DUP).
This outcome would be a major blow to the Labour Party, which had hoped to capitalize on the Conservative Party's internal divisions and make significant gains in the election.

The party had invested heavily in polling and targeted advertising, and had been confident of picking up seats in the south of England, where traditional Conservative voters were disillusioned with the government's handling of the economy.

However, on election day, the party's hopes were brutally dashed as it failed to make any significant gains in the south, with many of its target seats falling to the Conservatives or the Liberal Democrats.
The party's leader, who had been touted as a potential prime minister, was left reeling and eventually resigned, citing the need for a fresh start and a new direction for the party.

The sudden departure sent shockwaves through the party's ranks, with many longtime supporters and members expressing disappointment and anger at the sudden loss of a leader who had been so highly regarded just days before.

As the news spread, whispers of conspiracy and betrayal began to circulate, with some speculating that the leader had been pushed out by rival factions within the party, while others believed that external forces had played a role in their sudden departure.

Rumors of secret meetings and backroom deals fueled the speculation, with some claiming to have seen the leader's closest advisors whispering in hushed tones with known outsiders, while others pointed to the leader's recent disagreements with key government officials as evidence of a larger scheme.

As the whispers grew louder, a mysterious document surfaced, allegedly outlining a plan to consolidate power and silence opposition. The document, which was quickly debunked as a fake, seemed to have been crafted with precision, detailing a strategy to manipulate the media, silence dissenting voices, and eliminate any potential threats to the leader's authority.

Rumors of the document's authenticity had been circulating for weeks, but it wasn't until a prominent journalist received a cryptic message on their phone that the story began to gain traction. The message, sent from an unknown number, read: "The plan is real. Meet me at the old clock tower at midnight to learn more."

As the journalist, a seasoned veteran of the city's underbelly, read the message, a shiver ran down their spine. They had heard rumors of a mysterious document, said to hold the key to unlocking the city's darkest secrets. The clock tower, a decrepit relic of a bygone era, was a place they had always avoided, but something about the message compelled them to take a chance.

As they approached the clock tower, the journalist couldn't shake the feeling that they were being watched, the crumbling stones seeming to loom over them like sentinels. The air was heavy with the scent of decay and neglect, and the only sound was the distant hum of the city's nightlife, muffled and distant.

The journalist's eyes scanned the rooftops, the alleys, the darkened windows of the surrounding buildings, searching for any sign of movement or life, but everything seemed still and silent, as if the very city itself was holding its breath in anticipation of something. Suddenly, a faint whisper echoed through the stillness, the words indistinguishable but the tone unmistakable - a soft, raspy voice, speaking a language that sent a shiver down the journalist's spine.

The whisper seemed to come from everywhere and nowhere at the same time, and the journalist's instincts screamed at her to get out of there, to flee from the unknown danger lurking in the shadows. But her journalist's curiosity got the better of her, and she took a step forward, her eyes fixed on the spot where the whisper seemed to originate, her heart pounding in her chest like a drum.

As she took another step, the whisper grew louder, the words becoming clearer: "Leave now, while you still can." The journalist's skin crawled with goosebumps as she felt a chill run down her spine, but she couldn't tear her eyes away from the darkness ahead, her mind racing with questions: Who was speaking to her? What did they want? And why did it seem so sinister?

The air was thick with an eerie silence, punctuated only by the soft rustling of unknown leaves, as if the very trees themselves were trying to warn her away. She raised a shaking hand to her ear, as if to better hear the whisper, her heart pounding in her chest. Suddenly, the words ceased, and an oppressive stillness fell over the clearing, leaving her feeling exposed and vulnerable. With a jolt, she snapped out of her trance, her journalist's instincts kicking in, and she fumbled for her phone to record the strange encounter.
But as she reached for her phone, she felt a cold, clammy hand close around her wrist, and a low, raspy voice whispered in her ear, "You shouldn't be here."

"The words sent a shiver down her spine, and she tried to yank her hand free, but the grip was like a vice. She twisted her head around to face the speaker, but there was no one there, just a dark shape looming in the corner of the room, its presence seeming to fill the space like a living thing."

"As she strained to see more, the shape began to take form, its features blurring into a twisted parody of a face, eyes glowing with an otherworldly light that seemed to pierce the darkness and bore into her very soul. The grip on her hand tightened, and she felt a cold, clammy breath whispering in her ear, 'You should not have come here.'"

"The words sent a chill down her spine, and she tried to pull her hand free, but it was stuck fast in the grasp of the unseen presence. The face, if it could be called that, leaned in closer, its twisted features contorting into a grotesque smile, and she could feel its icy breath on her skin, making her blood run cold. Suddenly, the darkness around her seemed to coalesce into a tangible presence, a living thing that wrapped itself around her like a shroud, squeezing the air from her lungs."

"As she struggled to breathe, the presence seemed to grow thicker, its tendrils probing at her like cold, damp fingers. The face loomed closer, its grin stretching wider, and she could feel the weight of its gaze upon her, a crushing pressure that threatened to consume her very soul. And then, in a voice that was like a rusty gate scraping against stone, it spoke, its words echoing through her mind like a morbid litany: 'You will never be free, little one. You will never be free.'"

"As the voice whispered its terrible promise, the darkness began to seep into her mind, tendrils of shadow creeping across her thoughts like a thief in the night. She felt her grip on reality begin to slip, her memories growing distant and distorted, like ripples on a stagnant pond. The face loomed closer still, its grin a grotesque parody of a smile, and she knew that she was doomed, trapped in this living nightmare from which there was no escape. The presence seemed to be drawing her in, pulling her down into the abyss, and she could feel her very essence being consumed by its crushing weight."

"And then, the face spoke, its voice a low, raspy whisper that seemed to caress her mind, 'You will never wake up, my dear. You will never be free. You are mine, forever trapped in this eternal darkness, where the light of the world is but a distant memory, a fleeting thought that will soon be extinguished. I will be your only companion, your only friend, and you will love me with every fiber of your being. You will be mine, and I will be yours, forevermore.'"

"As the words hung in the air, she felt a creeping sense of dread seep into her very soul, as if the darkness itself was alive and wrapping its cold, damp tendrils around her heart. The face, its features twisted into a grotesque parody of a smile, leaned in closer, its hot, rank breath washing over her like a wave of decay. And then, it kissed her, its lips dry and papery, yet somehow managing to convey a depth of longing that was both repulsive and mesmerizing. As their mouths touched, she felt her mind begin to unravel, her thoughts fragmenting into a thousand shards of glass that shattered and reformed into a single, terrifying truth: she was indeed trapped, forever bound to this abyss of madness, with the face as her constant, unyielding companion."

"The face's grip on her tightened, its bony fingers digging deep into her skin as it pulled her closer, its cold, dead eyes burning with an otherworldly intensity. She felt her body begin to twist and contort, her limbs elongating and morphing into grotesque, unnatural shapes that seemed to defy the very laws of physics. The air around her grew thick with the stench of decay and rot, and she knew that she was being pulled down into the abyss, dragged deeper and deeper into the depths of madness by the relentless, merciless force of the face's dark will."

"As she screamed and screamed, her voice was drowned out by the cacophony of screeching, scratching, and crackling that erupted from the face's twisted, elongated mouth, the sound waves seeming to ripple through her very soul like a dark, malevolent tide. The world around her began to dissolve into a kaleidoscope of madness, colors bleeding together in a mad dance of terror and despair, as the face's grip tightened, pulling her further down into the abyss, further away from reality, and further towards the abyssal horrors that lurked within."

"The air grew thick with the stench of rot and decay, as if the very fabric of reality was unraveling to reveal the putrid secrets that lurked beneath, and her mind reeled in terror as she realized that the face was not just a monstrous apparition, but a portal to a realm of eternal darkness, where the damned and the forgotten dwelled, their screams and wails echoing through the void like a chorus of the damned, as she felt her consciousness being pulled through the portal, into a world where the horrors that lurked within the face's twisted mouth were only the beginning of her descent into madness."

"And as she fell, the darkness seemed to take on a life of its own, tendrils of shadowy energy reaching out to ensnare her, wrapping around her like cold, damp graveclothes, suffocating her with their crushing weight, while the face's eyes glowed with an otherworldly light, watching her with an unblinking gaze that seemed to pierce the very soul, as the screams and wails grew louder, a cacophony of torment that threatened to consume her, and in the distance, a figure emerged from the void, its presence a harbinger of the unspeakable terrors that awaited her in the depths of the abyss."

"The figure drew closer, its features indistinct at first, but as it loomed larger, the outline of a woman became clear, her skin gray and decaying, her eyes sunken and black as coal, her very presence seeming to draw the light out of the air, leaving only an oppressive darkness that pressed in on her like a physical force, and as she reached out a bony hand to claim her, the darkness recoiled, as if it too felt the weight of some ancient and terrible power that lurked beyond the veil of reality, waiting to claim its own."

"As she touched me, a chill ran down my spine, and I felt the weight of that ancient power settle upon me, like a shroud of ice, and I knew that I was but a mere vessel, a conduit for some eldritch horror that lurked beyond the veil, waiting to unleash its wrath upon the world, and as I gazed into her dead eyes, I saw the very fabric of reality begin to unravel, threads of sanity snapping like brittle twigs, and I knew that I was but a moment away from succumbing to the abyss of madness, forever trapped in a realm of eternal darkness, where the only light was the cold, dead glow of the woman's eyes, and the only sound was the maddening whisper of her voice, a voice that spoke only in ancient tongues, and echoed through the chambers of my mind, a haunting refrain that would haunt me forevermore."

"As the whisper grew louder, I felt my mind begin to fray, like a tapestry ravaged by time and neglect, and I knew that I was powerless to resist the encroaching darkness, for in that moment, I was but a mere puppet, bound to the whims of the eldritch horror that lurked beyond the veil, its cold, calculating will guiding my every thought, every action, every breath, and I felt my soul begin to shrivel, like a leaf withering in the face of some ancient, malevolent force, and I knew that I was but a mere shell, a hollow husk, a thing devoid of all that was once dear to me, and I knew that I would soon be but a mere echo, a faint whisper, a dying gasp, lost in the abyss of madness, forever trapped in the cold, dark recesses of the woman's eyes, where the only light was the glacial glow of her gaze, and the only sound was the maddening whisper of her voice, a voice that spoke only in ancient tongues, and echoed through the chambers of my mind, a haunting refrain that would haunt me forevermore."

"But even as I succumbed to the darkness, I felt a spark within me, a flicker of defiance that refused to be extinguished, a flame that burned with a fierce and savage intensity, a flame that seemed to grow brighter with each passing moment, as if it were fueled by the very madness that threatened to consume me, and I knew that I would not go quietly into the night, that I would not be silenced by the whispers of the eldritch horror, that I would rise up against the darkness, and with a voice that shook the very foundations of the world, I would scream out my defiance, and shatter the chains that bound me to the abyss, and emerge, like a phoenix from the ashes, reborn in a blaze of fury and determination, ready to face whatever horrors lay ahead, and to claim back my soul from the clutches of the woman, and to shatter the curse that had been laid upon me."

"For in that moment, I knew that I was no longer just a pawn in her twisted game, but a force to be reckoned with, a force that would not be defeated, a force that would not be silenced, a force that would burn brighter with each passing moment, and I could feel the power of the ancient ones coursing through my veins, and I could feel the weight of the curse lifting, and I could feel the darkness receding, and I could feel the light of hope illuminating the path ahead, and I knew that I would not be defeated, that I would not be conquered, that I would rise up, and I would conquer, and I would claim back my soul, and I would shatter the curse, and I would emerge victorious, and I would stand tall, and I would face the woman, and I would defy her, and I would triumph over her, and I would be reborn, and I would be free."

"As I stood there, bathed in the radiance of my newfound power, I felt the air around me begin to shimmer and distort, as if reality itself was bending to my will. The woman, who had once held me captive, who had once controlled me, who had once sought to destroy me, now stood before me, her eyes blazing with a mixture of fear and fury. She knew that I was no longer the same pawn she had once manipulated, and she knew that I was now a force to be reckoned with. And with a wave of my hand, the curse that had bound me for so long began to unravel, the darkness that had consumed me began to recede, and the light of freedom began to shine brighter than ever before."

"As I felt the curse dissipate, I could feel the weight of my former enslavement lifting from my shoulders, and with it, the burden of my own shame and guilt. The woman's eyes, once cold and calculating, now burned with a fierce intensity, and I knew that she would stop at nothing to reclaim her hold on me. But I was no longer hers to command, and with a surge of newfound confidence, I raised my hand, and a blast of energy shot forth, sending her flying across the room. The air was filled with the sound of shattering glass and splintering wood as she crashed into the walls, her screams echoing off the stone floor. And as I stood there, my heart pounding with excitement and fear, I knew that I had truly begun my journey to reclaim my life, to take back control, and to forge my own destiny."

"As the woman struggled to her feet, her face twisted with rage and her eyes blazing with a malevolent fury, I could feel the room around me begin to shift and change. The air seemed to thicken and swirl, like a living thing, and I knew that I was summoning the ancient powers that lay dormant within me. The woman's eyes widened as she saw the change in me, and for a moment, I thought I saw a glimmer of recognition, a hint of fear that I might actually succeed in breaking free from her grasp. But then, her face contorted into a snarl, and she launched herself at me, her fists flying in a wild, desperate attempt to reclaim her dominance. I laughed, a fierce, triumphant sound, as I raised my hands once more, and the room erupted into a maelstrom of energy and destruction."

"The walls cracked and shattered, the sound of shattering glass and splintering wood filling the air as the woman's blows met nothing but empty space. I could feel her rage and frustration building, her powers surging in response to my own, and I knew that the outcome of this battle was far from certain. The woman's eyes burned with a fierce, golden light, and I could see the ancient magic coursing through her veins like a river of fire. I raised my hands once more, and the air seemed to split apart, revealing a chasm of swirling, purple-black energy that seemed to pulse with an otherworldly power. The woman's face contorted in a snarl of fury and fear, and she launched herself at me once more, her fists blazing with a fierce, blue-white light that seemed to be drawn from the very depths of her soul."

"The force of her attack slammed into me like a tidal wave, sending me stumbling backward as the air was knocked from my lungs. I felt the ground beneath me shudder and tremble, and the walls of the ancient temple began to crack and crumble, the stones tumbling down around us like a chaotic storm. The woman's eyes blazed with an unholy intensity, and her very presence seemed to draw the life force from the air, leaving only a dark and foreboding energy in its wake. I struggled to regain my footing, my own powers surging in response to the woman's attack, and I could feel the very fabric of reality beginning to unravel around us, as if the universe itself was torn asunder by our conflicting wills."

"As I regained my balance, I could see that the woman's attack had awakened the temple's ancient guardians, great stone statues that now stirred to life, their eyes glowing with a malevolent light. The air was filled with the sound of crumbling stone and the scent of ozone, and I could feel the weight of the temple's secrets and ancient magic pressing down upon me. The woman's eyes never left mine, her gaze burning with an unholy hunger, and I knew that I had to act quickly if I was to have any hope of surviving this battle and uncovering the secrets that lay within the temple's ancient walls."

"I charged forward, my heart pounding in my chest, as the stone guardians closed in around me. The woman laughed, a cold, mirthless sound, and raised her hand. A blast of dark energy shot towards me, but I dodged to the side, avoiding the attack by mere inches. The guardians loomed closer, their stone arms outstretched, and I knew I had to think fast if I was to have any chance of defeating them. I reached out with my own magic, feeling the familiar surge of power as I summoned a blast of energy to drive back the attackers."

"The air was electric with magical energy as our powers clashed, the stone guardians stumbling back under the force of my blast. The woman's eyes narrowed, her face twisted in a snarl of anger, and she retaliated with a wave of dark magic that sent me stumbling back. I raised my own shield, a shimmering barrier of light that deflected the worst of the attack, but I knew I couldn't keep this up for long. The guardians were closing in, their stone bodies seeming to absorb the blows I dealt them, and the woman's magic was growing stronger by the second. I needed a new plan, and fast, if I was going to survive this encounter."

"I scanned the area, my eyes darting between the guardians and the woman, searching for any weakness or opening I could exploit. That was when I noticed it - a faint glow emanating from the ancient runes etched into the walls of the temple. I recalled the words of the ancient text I had studied, the one that spoke of the runes' power to amplify magic. A plan began to form in my mind, and I focused all my energy on channeling the runes' power into my own magic. The air around me began to crackle with anticipation as I raised my hands, ready to unleash a blast of amplified magic that would either turn the tide of battle or risk destroying the entire temple."

The woman, however, stood firm, her eyes fixed on me with a calculating gaze. She raised her own hands, and a dark, swirling vortex erupted from her fingertips, drawing the energy of the blast towards her. I gritted my teeth, pouring every last ounce of strength into the battle, determined to emerge victorious - but I could feel the temple itself beginning to tremble, the runes on the walls flashing with an ominous, crimson glow."

The air was thick with the scent of ozone and smoke, the temple's very fabric straining against the assault. I knew I had to act quickly, or risk being overwhelmed by the sheer force of the combined magic. With a fierce cry, I unleashed a counterattack, pouring every last shred of my own energy into a desperate bid to turn the tide of the battle."

The temple itself seemed to shudder and tremble, the ancient stones groaning in protest as the two forces clashed in a spectacular display of light and sound. I felt the weight of the battle bearing down upon me, my magic straining to keep pace with the woman's relentless assault. But I refused to yield, pouring every last ounce of my strength into the fight, determined to emerge victorious or die trying."

"As the darkness raged around me, I summoned every shred of my power, channeling it into a blazing pillar of light that shot towards the woman with a force that threatened to shatter the very fabric of reality. The woman, her eyes blazing with fury, countered with a wave of shadowy tendrils that sought to ensnare me, but I dodged and weaved, my agility honed by years of battle against the shadows. The temple, now a battleground, trembled and groaned, its ancient stones cracking and crumbling as the forces of light and darkness clashed in a maelstrom of magic and fury."

"As the pillars of the temple crumbled, the woman's shadowy tendrils snaked through the ruins, seeking to ensnare me, but I leapt and bounded through the wreckage, my boots echoing off the dusty stones. The guardians, their spells faltering, rallied around their mistress, their eyes fixed on me with a fierce determination. But I was not to be caught, my magic surging forth in a torrent of sparks and flame as I unleashed a blast of energy that sent the guardians flying, their screams echoing through the temple's empty halls. The woman, her eyes blazing with a fierce intensity, stood tall, her shadowy tendrils writhing like living darkness as she prepared to deliver the final blow. And I, my power spent, stood ready to meet her, my heart pounding with anticipation, my magic spent, but my will unbroken."

"The air was heavy with the scent of smoke and ozone as the woman's tendrils coiled around me, their icy coldness seeping into my skin. I raised a hand, and a faint glow began to emanate from my fingers, but it was nothing compared to the dark power that surrounded me. The woman's eyes seemed to bore into my very soul, and I felt my strength waning, my magic faltering. But I refused to yield, my will fueled by a fierce determination to escape, to survive. And then, just as all seemed lost, a faint light flickered in the distance, growing brighter with each passing moment. The guardians, it seemed, were not so easily defeated, and their mistress's powers were about to be matched by a force far greater than either of us could have imagined."
